# Coverage exclusions — regex patterns matched against lines of the
# raw `go test -coverprofile` output, applied before the 100% gate.
#
# Lines starting with `#` are comments. Empty lines are ignored.
# Anchor each pattern at the start of the path (`^github.com/...`) so
# it only matches the intended file.
#
# Each entry MUST be paired with a comment explaining why the line is
# unreachable in practice. Add a new entry only after refactoring is
# more invasive than the gain in test confidence.

# cmd/slack-acp/main.go is the entry-point wiring: flag parsing,
# signal handling, dependency assembly. The internal/* packages
# carry the testable logic; main.go is a thin adapter that would
# need a full subprocess-based smoke harness to exercise. Excluded
# wholesale, like sibling project poe-acp does for its own main.go.
^github.com/kfet/slack-acp/cmd/slack-acp/main\.go:

# Two defensive branches in acpclient.Start:
#
#   stdin, err := cmd.StdinPipe()
#   if err != nil { ... }
#   stdout, err := cmd.StdoutPipe()
#   if err != nil { ... }
#
# StdinPipe / StdoutPipe error only when the corresponding cmd.Stdin
# or cmd.Stdout was already set. Start never does that — the cmd is
# constructed inline by exec.CommandContext and the only fields we
# touch are .Dir, .Env, .Stderr — so both branches are structurally
# unreachable in production. Earlier we routed these through
# package-level pipeFn indirections so tests could override them, but
# that was contortion of production code purely to satisfy the
# coverage gate. The .covignore approach (matching poe-acp) keeps
# Start straightforward.
^github.com/kfet/slack-acp/internal/acpclient/agent\.go:123\.
^github.com/kfet/slack-acp/internal/acpclient/agent\.go:127\.
